{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518307"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:03:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:03:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12910"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12910"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.04,0.15,0.05,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110872"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5348"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12910"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93044"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"212"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41884"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110872"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of severe headaches. She experiences three to five episodes each month. She describes her headaches as severe and throbbing, often localised to the left side of her head. Each episode lasts for several hours. The pain is frequently accompanied by nausea and vomiting. Physical activity tends to exacerbate the pain. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Initially, she treated her headaches with ibuprofen and metoclopramide, but these medications now provide no relief. She has recently started using sumatriptan during acute attacks with some improvement. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is unremarkable between episodes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gabapentin","Valproate","Eletriptan","Naproxen","Propranolol"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classical migraine features meeting diagnostic criteria: recurrent severe, throbbing, unilateral headaches lasting hours, accompanied by nausea and vomiting, and worsened by physical activity. With more than two episodes monthly requiring acute treatment, she meets the threshold for prophylactic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next treatment. It is a first-line prophylactic medication for migraine prevention with good evidence for efficacy. As a beta-blocker, it is generally well-tolerated and would be suitable for this young woman with no significant medical history or contraindications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGabapentin\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for migraine prophylaxis but has less robust evidence compared to propranolol and is typically reserved for patients who have failed or cannot tolerate first-line options. While it may have some efficacy, it is not considered a first-line prophylactic agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValproate\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective migraine prophylactic but would not be the most appropriate choice for a woman of childbearing age due to its significant teratogenic risks. It should be avoided in women who could become pregnant unless no other options are suitable and appropriate contraception is ensured. Despite having evidence for efficacy, the safety concerns make it unsuitable as a first choice in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEletriptan\u003C/strong\u003E is another triptan medication used for acute migraine treatment, similar to the sumatriptan she is already using effectively. Triptans are not used for prophylaxis; they are only for aborting acute attacks. Adding another triptan would not address the need to reduce attack frequency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaproxen\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug used for acute migraine treatment. Like ibuprofen, which has already failed for this patient, it would not be appropriate as prophylaxis. Additionally, frequent use of NSAIDs can lead to medication overuse headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther first-line prophylactic options include topiramate and amitriptyline. Additional medications such as pregabalin, venlafaxine, and sodium valproate can be used for migraine prophylaxis, though they may have less evidence to support their use compared to established first-line agents. The choice of prophylactic agent should consider patient-specific factors including comorbidities, contraindications, and patient preference.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Migraine prophylaxis should be considered when patients experience three or more episodes per month or require acute treatment on more than two to four days per month.","Propranolol is a first-line prophylactic medication for migraine prevention in patients without contraindications.","Triptans are effective for acute migraine treatment but are not used for prophylaxis."],"references":["Jenkins B. Migraine management. Aust Prescr [Internet]. 2020 Oct [cited 2023 Jul 14];43(5):148. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7572189/ doi: 10.18773/austprescr.2020.047","Rizzoli P, Mullaly WJ. Headache. Am J Med [Internet]. 2018 Jan [cited 2023 Jul 13];131(1):17-24. Available from: https://www.amjmed.com/article/S0002-9343(17)30932-4/fulltext doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2017.09.005","Approach to the treatment of migraines. In: Therapeutic guidelines [online]. Accessed 2025 Aug 4. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93044"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12910"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93044"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-04T19:54:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-04T19:55:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5348"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110872"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null